{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0d962611-dec5-494c-8c5e-3dcf1f50af84","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workloads need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, you can also try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk\n```\nThis carries forward workloads that were installed for your previous SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"93365659-f361-4b62-beec-5dded32102e9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":258,"requestId":"7FD2:195805:5FDE7DB:68AA396:69F15624"},"id":"0441ba4d-5658-454f-8080-be9727a2907f","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:56.309Z","parentId":"0ff2130e-07c5-4ada-9f6f-3a0480a4bbb2"}
